          "title": "God as the agent of destruction — the chapter's most difficult claim",
          "body": "Lamentations 2 is the most theologically unsettling chapter in the book precisely because it refuses to let the reader identify Babylon as the real cause of Jerusalem's fall. The verbs of destruction in verses 1-9 all have the same subject: the Lord. He covered, cast, swallowed up, thrown down, cut off, drawn back, burned, bent His bow, poured out His wrath, violently treated His tabernacle, destroyed His appointed meeting place, caused to be forgotten, despised, rejected, abandoned, delivered into the hand of the enemy, stretched out a measuring line, determined the destruction. By the time the poet reaches the climactic claim of verse 5 — 'The Lord has become like an enemy' — he has been preparing the reader for fifteen clauses. The theological tradition of the ancient Near East explained catastrophe by the anger of defeated gods or the incompetence of divine protectors. The poet refuses both options: Israel's God is not defeated, and He is not absent. He is the architect of the demolition."
