          "title": "The prophet's witness — grief that cannot be comforted",
          "body": "The chapter's emotional center is the poet's first-person eruption in verses 11-13. Until this point he has described destruction from the outside; now he names what it costs him to witness it. His eyes fail because of tears. His spirit is troubled. His heart is poured out on the earth. And what breaks him is not the political disaster or the architectural ruin — it is children and infants fainting in the streets, asking their mothers for grain and wine and dying on their bosoms (2:11-12). Then he turns to address the city directly and finds himself speechless: 'How shall I admonish you? To what shall I compare you?' The question is not rhetorical — he genuinely cannot find a comparison adequate to the destruction. 'For your ruin is as vast as the sea; who can heal you?' (2:13). The unanswerable quality of this question is the chapter's emotional logic: when no human comfort is proportionate to the grief, the only remaining direction is God."
