        "body": "Verses 6-9 identify the most devastating specific losses within the general destruction of verses 1-5: not buildings but *instruments of divine-human encounter*. The tabernacle (*sokh*, literally a leafy booth or shelter) is treated like a *gan* — a temporary garden enclosure, not a permanent dwelling. The mocking parallel is with the Feast of Booths (Sukkot), in which Israel dwelt in temporary shelters precisely to remember their wilderness dependence. Now God's own sanctuary is reduced to the status of that wilderness shelter — and then demolished even that.\n\nThe word *moed* (appointed feast/meeting place) appears three times in verses 6-7 and returns at 2:22. Its double meaning is the key: *moed* is both the sacred assembly (Leviticus 23) and the appointed meeting point between God and His people. When the appointed feasts are 'forgotten' (2:6), it is not merely the cancellation of holidays; it is the severance of the structured times and spaces through which God had covenanted to meet His people. The Sabbath — the weekly sign of the Mosaic covenant (Exodus 31:13) — is included in the forgetting. The liturgical calendar has gone dark.\n\nThe prophet and king appear together in verse 6 as the twin officers of covenanted leadership — 'king and priest' (*melekh* and *kohen*). Their joint 'despising' (*naats*) by God signals that neither the royal covenant (2 Samuel 7) nor the priestly covenant (Numbers 25:12-13) is functioning as a buffer. Verse 9 then adds the law (*torah*) and prophetic vision (*chazon*): 'the law is no more; her prophets find no vision from the Lord.' The four channels through which God communicated His will to His people — royal decree, priestly instruction, written law, prophetic oracle — are simultaneously closed.\n\nThis quadruple silencing is what makes the situation of chapter 2 categorically different from ordinary military defeat. Nations lose wars and rebuild. But when the law is gone, the prophetic word is withdrawn, the temple is destroyed, and the covenantal calendar is dismantled simultaneously, the entire framework of structured relationship between God and His people has been removed. This is the exile as theological crisis, not merely as geopolitical displacement. The exiles in Babylon did not merely lack a homeland; they lacked every institutional mediation of God's presence. The question 'how can we sing the Lord's song in a foreign land?' (Psalm 137:4) is not nostalgia; it is a genuine theological problem.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Moed* (appointed time/assembly, 2:6 ×2, 7, 22) is the critical word — its destruction represents not merely liturgical disruption but covenantal-relational severance. *Torah* (2:9) is not merely legal code but the entirety of God's revealed instruction; its absence is the absence of God's communicative presence. *Chazon* (prophetic vision, 2:9) is the technical term for the revelatory reception that authorizes prophetic speech (Amos 1:1; Isaiah 1:1) — its withdrawal means the prophetic office is hollow."
